  "publisher": "dc",
  "about": "Talia al Ghul (; Arabic: تالية الغول, Arabic pronunciation: [taːlijja al.ɣuːl]) is a fictional character appearing in American comic books published by DC Comics. The character was created by writer Dennis O'Neil and artist Bob Brown, and first appeared in Detective Comics #411 (May 1971). Commonly associated with Batman and having been characterized as a morally ambiguous anti-heroine and supervillain, Talia stands as one of the character's most enduring love interests and female adversaries.\nTalia is the daughter of the eco-terrorist and supervillain, Ra's al Ghul. Born as a high-ranking elite of the League of Assassins, Talia followed in her father's footsteps, becoming a master assassin, one of the world's greatest spymasters, and heiress but is passed over by her chauvensic father as his successor. Seeking to elevate her status, she first sought a suitable male partner and produce a son but ultimately falls in love with Batman, testing her loyalties to either and her subsequent romatic entanglements with Batman leads to the birth of their son, Damian Wayne. Eventually taking a darker turn as she branched out, she has been a leading figure of the Secret Society of Super-Villains, the leader of the League of Assassins,  the founder of her own secret society, Leviathan, and eventually established as the leader of the League of Shadows by Ra's himself.\nSince the character's inception, Talia's character has been noted to be among Batman's most compelling villains inspite of constrasting portrayals, noted for her evolution from being a \"Bond-girl archetype\" into a pivotal and complex character and haing ambiguous motivations. However, criticism of the character's originates from elements of orientalism including being characereized within the dragon lady stereotype and being encoded as \"ethnic\" and \"foreign\" with no definitive identity due to Ra's conceptual creation by Neal Adams.\nTalia has been featured in various media adaptations. The character was voiced by Helen Slater and Olivia Hussey in the DC Animated Universe, which became her first appearances in media other than comic books. The character was subsequently portrayed by Marion Cotillard in the 2012 film The Dark Knight Rises and by Lexa Doig in the Arrowverse television series Arrow.",
  "note": null,
  "source": "dc"
